<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n20230i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n20" href="#n20230i">N20 (VI.B.13)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n20all.htm#n20230i"> 230(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Urthona spirit / Luvah emotion / Urizen reason / Tharmas body <font face="wake">X</font></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">It was clear to him that the chief personages of his mythological system (such as Urthona, the spirit, Luvah, the emotion, and Urizen, the reason) were three of the Four Beings of the Revelation. Yet he was not satisfied, for the fourth was lacking &hellip; He added a new personage in Vala, wanting to make the four Regents, and entitled it Tharmas, from the Hindu Tarmas, meaning &ldquo;desire,&rdquo; to represent the body, so to complete a new Fourfold Man. <small> Darrell Figgis, <a name="DFPW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#DFPW"><cite title="source">The Paintings of William Blake</cite></a> (1925) 43</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c13023c" href="c13all.htm#c13023c">VI.C.13:023(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
